H.B. 92
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Feb 10, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH30043-MU-22
Short Title: NC Digital Assets Investments Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Ross.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO AUTHORIZE THE STATE TREASURER TO INVEST IN QUALIFYING
3 DIGITAL ASSETS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. Article 6 of Chapter 147 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
6 a new section to read:
7 "§ 147-69.2E. Investments in digital assets.
8 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
9 (1) Digital asset. – A virtual currency, cryptocurrency, native electronic asset,
10 stablecoin, nonfungible token, or any other asset that is only digital and that
11 confers economic, proprietary, or access rights or powers.
12 (2) Exchange-traded product. – A security, as defined in G.S. 78A-2, that meets
13 any of the following requirements:
14 a. The security is listed, or authorized for listing, on the New York Stock
15 Exchange, the American Stock Exchange, or the National Association
16 of Securities Dealers Automated Quotations national market system
17 (NASDAQ), or any successor to these entities.
18 b. The security is listed, or authorized for listing, on a national securities
19 exchange or system, or on a tier or segment of the exchange or system,
20 designated by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission
21 in 17 C.F.R. § 230.146(b).
22 c. The security is listed, or authorized for listing, on a national securities
23 exchange or system, or on a tier or segment of the exchange or system,
24 that has listing standards that the North Carolina Secretary of State, on
25 its own initiative or on the basis of an application, determines by rule
26 are substantially similar to the listing standards applicable to securities
27 described in sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
28 d. The security is a security of the same issuer that is equal in seniority
29 to, or that is senior to, a security described in sub-subdivisions a.
30 through c. of this subdivision.
31 (3) Private key. – A unique element of cryptographic data used for signing
32 transactions on a blockchain that is known to the owner of the unique element.
33 (4) Secure custody solution. – A technological product or a blended product and
34 service that has all of the following characteristics:
35 a. The private keys that secure digital assets are exclusively known and
36 accessible by the State Treasurer.
*DRH30043-MU-22*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. The private keys that secure digital assets are exclusively contained
2 within an encrypted environment and are accessible only via
3 end-to-end encrypted channels.
4 c. The private keys that secure digital assets are never contained by,
5 accessible by, or controllable via a smartphone.
6 d. Any hardware that contains the private keys that secure digital assets
7 is maintained in at least two geographically diversified, specially
8 designated secure data centers.
9 e. The secure custody solution enforces a multi-party governance
10 structure for authorizing transactions, enforces user access controls,
11 and logs all user-initiated actions.
12 f. The provider of the secure custody solution has implemented a disaster
13 recovery protocol that ensures customer access to digital assets in the
14 event the provider becomes unavailable.
15 g. The secure custody solution undergoes regular code audits and
16 penetration testing from audit firms, and any identified vulnerabilities
17 are promptly remedied.
18 (b) The State Treasurer may invest the cash of the funds described in G.S. 147-69.1(b)
19 and G.S. 147-69.2(a) in digital assets that satisfy both of the following requirements:
20 (1) The digital assets are an exchange-traded product.
21 (2) The average market capitalization of the digital assets over the preceding 12
22 months is at least seven hundred fifty billion dollars ($750,000,000,000), as
23 determined by the State Treasurer using a commercially reasonable method.
24 (c) An investment in digital assets from any of these funds shall not exceed, in the
25 aggregate, ten percent (10%) of the balance of the fund at the time of the investment.
26 (d) If the State Treasurer chooses to internally manage any digital assets, the State
27 Treasurer shall use a secure custody solution."
28 SECTION 2. G.S. 147-69.1 reads as rewritten:
29 "§ 147-69.1. Investments authorized for General Fund and Highway Funds assets.
30 (a) The Governor and Council of State, with the advice and assistance of the State
31 Treasurer, shall adopt such rules and regulations as shall be necessary and appropriate to
32 implement the provisions of this section.
33 (b) This section applies to funds held by the State Treasurer to the credit of:of each of the
34 following:
35 (1) The General Fund;Fund.
36 (2) The Highway Fund and Highway Trust Fund.
37 (c) It shall be the duty of the The State Treasurer to shall invest the cash of the funds
38 enumerated in subsection (b) of this section in excess of the amount required to meet the current
39 needs and demands on such these funds, selecting from among the following:
40 …
41 (11) Digital assets in accordance with G.S. 147-69.2E.
42 (d) Unless otherwise provided by law, the interest or income received and accruing from
43 all deposits or investments of such the cash balances shall be paid into the State's General Fund,
44 except that all interest or income received and accruing on the monthly balance of the Highway
45 Fund and Highway Trust Fund shall be paid into the State Highway Fund and Highway Trust
46 Fund. The cash balances of the several funds may be combined for deposit or investment
47 purposes; and when such combined deposits or investments are made, the interest or income
48 received and accruing from all deposits or investments shall be prorated among the funds in
49 conformity with applicable law and law, including the rules and regulations adopted by the
50 Governor and Council of State.
51 …."
